{"type":"message","id":"0bf99f34","parentId":"af699830","timestamp":"2026-03-20T02:58:12.258Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"199\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"840470136\",\n  \"sender\": \"🟢Crypto Rixh🟢\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-20 02:58 UTC\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"🟢Crypto Rixh🟢 (840470136)\",\n  \"id\": \"840470136\",\n  \"name\": \"🟢Crypto Rixh🟢\",\n  \"username\": \"CryptoRixh\"\n}\n```\n\nHow can current and future users get to configure and message their agents on telegram ? I have a bot token for Dixie: 7225780511:AAH9B0StUH7vd26ewDXpuB698YB1l60OXbc, and for Willow: 8562090487:AAGTrtdu8hP3WV4UYjldnCES-e9f2_dxHF0, something like the user messages the bot on telegram , receives a “token” sends it to the app chat and configure their account for telegram usage , or if there’s a better way provided by openclaw"}],"timestamp":1773975492250}}
{"type":"message","id":"a69d96d2","parentId":"0bf99f34","timestamp":"2026-03-20T02:58:27.006Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking about how to set up Telegram messaging for their StudyClaw agents. They have two bot tokens - one for Dixie and one for Willow. They want a flow where users can:\n1. Message the bot on Telegram\n2. Receive a token\n3. Send it to the app to configure their account for Telegram\n\nThis is a common pattern. Let me think about the options:\n\n1. **OpenClaw's built-in Telegram integration** - OpenClaw already has Telegram support. Users can message the bot directly if they're in the allowed list.\n\n2. **Custom flow** - Build a custom Telegram bot that links to StudyClaw users\n\nLet me first check how OpenClaw handles Telegram to see what's already possible, then suggest the best approach.\n\nThe user has OpenClaw running, and there's already a Telegram channel configured. Let me see how it works.","thinkingSignature":"ed18f9a2d35c0bd7d496f54f594bddfe59aa5d7324b669809bb8b65a66c9ed9a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vyrk967zj5wg_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -A 20 '\"telegram\"' /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/openclaw.json | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":68,"output":228,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":45300,"totalTokens":45596,"cost":{"input":0.000020399999999999998,"output":0.0002736,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0.005436,"total":0.00573}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773975492255}}
{"type":"message","id":"38ddb141","parentId":"a69d96d2","timestamp":"2026-03-20T02:58:27.094Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_vyrk967zj5wg_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"telegram\": {\n      \"enabled\": true,\n      \"dmPolicy\": \"pairing\",\n      \"botToken\": \"1924234585:AAHJ1whQdLwl2rZ-e6v9En0_el0RevFiQVg\",\n      \"groupPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n      \"streaming\": \"partial\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"gateway\": {\n    \"port\": 18789,\n    \"mode\": \"local\",\n    \"bind\": \"lan\",\n    \"controlUi\": {\n      \"allowedOrigins\": [\n        \"https://3.144.253.238\",\n        \"http://3.148.233.46\",\n        \"*\"\n      ]\n    },\n    \"auth\": {\n      \"mode\": \"token\",\n--\n      \"telegram\": {\n        \"enabled\": true\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":26,"aggregated":"\"telegram\": {\n      \"enabled\": true,\n      \"dmPolicy\": \"pairing\",\n      \"botToken\": \"1924234585:AAHJ1whQdLwl2rZ-e6v9En0_el0RevFiQVg\",\n      \"groupPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n      \"streaming\": \"partial\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"gateway\": {\n    \"port\": 18789,\n    \"mode\": \"local\",\n    \"bind\": \"lan\",\n    \"controlUi\": {\n      \"allowedOrigins\": [\n        \"https://3.144.253.238\",\n        \"http://3.148.233.46\",\n        \"*\"\n      ]\n    },\n    \"auth\": {\n      \"mode\": \"token\",\n--\n      \"telegram\": {\n        \"enabled\": true\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773975507089}}
{"type":"message","id":"a7fa0c76","parentId":"38ddb141","timestamp":"2026-03-20T02:58:38.743Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So OpenClaw has Telegram integration with:\n- `dmPolicy: \"pairing\"` - This is the key! It means users can pair their Telegram with their account via a token\n- A bot token already configured (1924234585:AAHJ1whQdLwl2rZ-e6v9En0_el0RevFiQVg)\n\nThe pairing flow works like this:\n1. User messages the bot on Telegram\n2. Bot sends back a pairing code/token\n3. User enters that code in the app to link their Telegram\n\nThis is exactly what the user wants! Let me explain this to them.","thinkingSignature":"f46fa03cdf2bb9dd1d4cd7a4e4db54204b9b9f5d3b01c06cbbfa4f7f0d1ca41a"},{"type":"text","text":"OpenClaw already has this built in! The `dmPolicy: \"pairing\"` setting handles exactly that flow.\n\n**How it works:**\n1. User messages the bot → gets a pairing code\n2. User enters code in the StudyClaw app\n3. Telegram gets linked to their account\n\n**Your current bot:** `1924234585:AAHJ1whQdLwl2rZ-e6v9En0_el0RevFiQVg`\n\nThat's already set up for **your** main agent. For the student agents (Dixie, Willow), you'd need to either:\n\n**Option A:** Use the same bot (all users pair through one bot, but their sessions are separated)\n\n**Option B:** Use your separate bot tokens per agent (but you'd need to configure each in OpenClaw)\n\n**Best approach:** Use the main OpenClaw bot for all — students message it, get a unique token, pair it in the app. Their chats route to their own agent automatically.\n\nWant me to test the pairing flow with one of your accounts? Or do you want me to configure the separate Dixie/Willow bots?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":32323,"output":368,"cacheRead":13464,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46155,"cost":{"input":0.0096969,"output":0.0004416,"cacheRead":0.00040391999999999994,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.01054242}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773975507097}}
{"type":"message","id":"ddd1c2d5","parentId":"a7fa0c76","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:03.520Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"201\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"840470136\",\n  \"sender\": \"🟢Crypto Rixh🟢\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-20 03:02 UTC\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"🟢Crypto Rixh🟢 (840470136)\",\n  \"id\": \"840470136\",\n  \"name\": \"🟢Crypto Rixh🟢\",\n  \"username\": \"CryptoRixh\"\n}\n```\n\nAll users who chose Willow during onboarding will message their agents same bot but their sessions are separate. Same goes for Dixie they will message their respective bot and have separate isolated conversations with their bot"}],"timestamp":1773975723513}}
{"type":"message","id":"7ed73c06","parentId":"ddd1c2d5","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:16.766Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants separate bots for each agent:\n- All Willow users → bot token 8562090487:AAGTrtdu8hP3WV4UYjldnCES-e9f2_dxHF0\n- All Dixie users → bot token 7225780511:AAH9B0StUH7vd26ewDXpuB698YB1l60OXbc\n\nThis is more complex because OpenClaw currently only has one telegram bot configured globally. To have separate bots for different agents, we'd need to either:\n\n1. Configure multiple telegram accounts in OpenClaw (not sure if supported)\n2. Run multiple OpenClaw gateway instances\n3. Use a different approach\n\nLet me check OpenClaw docs to see if it supports multiple telegram bots.","thinkingSignature":"a9a358b492595066f4ecd4ec47c9695358c748e0e7c546e747edaa0800fff93f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_i6s381kmvdxh_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/ubuntu/.nvm/versions/node/v24.14.0/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md | head -100"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":68,"output":217,"cacheRead":45076,"cacheWrite":874,"totalTokens":46235,"cost":{"input":0.000020399999999999998,"output":0.0002604,"cacheRead":0.00135228,"cacheWrite":0.00010487999999999999,"total":0.0017379599999999998}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773975723518}}
{"type":"message","id":"cd9a3786","parentId":"7ed73c06","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:16.787Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_i6s381kmvdxh_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nsummary: \"Telegram bot support status, capabilities, and configuration\"\nread_when:\n  - Working on Telegram features or webhooks\ntitle: \"Telegram\"\n---\n\n# Telegram (Bot API)\n\nStatus: production-ready for bot DMs + groups via grammY. Long polling is the default mode; webhook mode is optional.\n\n<CardGroup cols={3}>\n  <Card title=\"Pairing\" icon=\"link\" href=\"/channels/pairing\">\n    Default DM policy for Telegram is pairing.\n  </Card>\n  <Card title=\"Channel troubleshooting\" icon=\"wrench\" href=\"/channels/troubleshooting\">\n    Cross-channel diagnostics and repair playbooks.\n  </Card>\n  <Card title=\"Gateway configuration\" icon=\"settings\" href=\"/gateway/configuration\">\n    Full channel config patterns and examples.\n  </Card>\n</CardGroup>\n\n## Quick setup\n\n<Steps>\n  <Step title=\"Create the bot token in BotFather\">\n    Open Telegram and chat with **@BotFather** (confirm the handle is exactly `@BotFather`).\n\n    Run `/newbot`, follow prompts, and save the token.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Configure token and DM policy\">\n\n```json5\n{\n  channels: {\n    telegram: {\n      enabled: true,\n      botToken: \"123:abc\",\n      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n      groups: { \"*\": { requireMention: true } },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\n    Env fallback: `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=...` (default account only).\n    Telegram does **not** use `openclaw channels login telegram`; configure token in config/env, then start gateway.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Start gateway and approve first DM\">\n\n```bash\nopenclaw gateway\nopenclaw pairing list telegram\nopenclaw pairing approve telegram <CODE>\n```\n\n    Pairing codes expire after 1 hour.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Add the bot to a group\">\n    Add the bot to your group, then set `channels.telegram.groups` and `groupPolicy` to match your access model.\n  </Step>\n</Steps>\n\n<Note>\nToken resolution order is account-aware. In practice, config values win over env fallback, and `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` only applies to the default account.\n</Note>\n\n## Telegram side settings\n\n<AccordionGroup>\n  <Accordion title=\"Privacy mode and group visibility\">\n    Telegram bots default to **Privacy Mode**, which limits what group messages they receive.\n\n    If the bot must see all group messages, either:\n\n    - disable privacy mode via `/setprivacy`, or\n    - make the bot a group admin.\n\n    When toggling privacy mode, remove + re-add the bot in each group so Telegram applies the change.\n\n  </Accordion>\n\n  <Accordion title=\"Group permissions\">\n    Admin status is controlled in Telegram group settings.\n\n    Admin bots receive all group messages, which is useful for always-on group behavior.\n\n  </Accordion>\n\n  <Accordion title=\"Helpful BotFather toggles\">\n\n    - `/setjoingroups` to allow/deny group adds\n    - `/setprivacy` for group visibility behavior"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":14,"aggregated":"---\nsummary: \"Telegram bot support status, capabilities, and configuration\"\nread_when:\n  - Working on Telegram features or webhooks\ntitle: \"Telegram\"\n---\n\n# Telegram (Bot API)\n\nStatus: production-ready for bot DMs + groups via grammY. Long polling is the default mode; webhook mode is optional.\n\n<CardGroup cols={3}>\n  <Card title=\"Pairing\" icon=\"link\" href=\"/channels/pairing\">\n    Default DM policy for Telegram is pairing.\n  </Card>\n  <Card title=\"Channel troubleshooting\" icon=\"wrench\" href=\"/channels/troubleshooting\">\n    Cross-channel diagnostics and repair playbooks.\n  </Card>\n  <Card title=\"Gateway configuration\" icon=\"settings\" href=\"/gateway/configuration\">\n    Full channel config patterns and examples.\n  </Card>\n</CardGroup>\n\n## Quick setup\n\n<Steps>\n  <Step title=\"Create the bot token in BotFather\">\n    Open Telegram and chat with **@BotFather** (confirm the handle is exactly `@BotFather`).\n\n    Run `/newbot`, follow prompts, and save the token.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Configure token and DM policy\">\n\n```json5\n{\n  channels: {\n    telegram: {\n      enabled: true,\n      botToken: \"123:abc\",\n      dmPolicy: \"pairing\",\n      groups: { \"*\": { requireMention: true } },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\n    Env fallback: `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=...` (default account only).\n    Telegram does **not** use `openclaw channels login telegram`; configure token in config/env, then start gateway.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Start gateway and approve first DM\">\n\n```bash\nopenclaw gateway\nopenclaw pairing list telegram\nopenclaw pairing approve telegram <CODE>\n```\n\n    Pairing codes expire after 1 hour.\n\n  </Step>\n\n  <Step title=\"Add the bot to a group\">\n    Add the bot to your group, then set `channels.telegram.groups` and `groupPolicy` to match your access model.\n  </Step>\n</Steps>\n\n<Note>\nToken resolution order is account-aware. In practice, config values win over env fallback, and `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` only applies to the default account.\n</Note>\n\n## Telegram side settings\n\n<AccordionGroup>\n  <Accordion title=\"Privacy mode and group visibility\">\n    Telegram bots default to **Privacy Mode**, which limits what group messages they receive.\n\n    If the bot must see all group messages, either:\n\n    - disable privacy mode via `/setprivacy`, or\n    - make the bot a group admin.\n\n    When toggling privacy mode, remove + re-add the bot in each group so Telegram applies the change.\n\n  </Accordion>\n\n  <Accordion title=\"Group permissions\">\n    Admin status is controlled in Telegram group settings.\n\n    Admin bots receive all group messages, which is useful for always-on group behavior.\n\n  </Accordion>\n\n  <Accordion title=\"Helpful BotFather toggles\">\n\n    - `/setjoingroups` to allow/deny group adds\n    - `/setprivacy` for group visibility behavior","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773975736784}}
