{"type":"message","id":"a1998df9","parentId":"3d6930c0","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:21.402Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_mzqgn7o6wrox_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"enabled\": true\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"channels\": {\n    \"telegram\": {\n      \"enabled\": true,\n      \"dmPolicy\": \"pairing\",\n      \"botToken\": \"1924234585:AAHJ1whQdLwl2rZ-e6v9En0_el0RevFiQVg\",\n      \"groupPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n      \"streaming\": \"partial\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"gateway\": {\n    \"port\": 18789,\n    \"mode\": \"local\",\n    \"bind\": \"lan\",\n    \"controlUi\": {\n      \"allowedOrigins\": [\n        \"https://3.144.253.238\","}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"\"enabled\": true\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"channels\": {\n    \"telegram\": {\n      \"enabled\": true,\n      \"dmPolicy\": \"pairing\",\n      \"botToken\": \"1924234585:AAHJ1whQdLwl2rZ-e6v9En0_el0RevFiQVg\",\n      \"groupPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n      \"streaming\": \"partial\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"gateway\": {\n    \"port\": 18789,\n    \"mode\": \"local\",\n    \"bind\": \"lan\",\n    \"controlUi\": {\n      \"allowedOrigins\": [\n        \"https://3.144.253.238\",","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773975741399}}
{"type":"message","id":"729dae5c","parentId":"a1998df9","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:41.137Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the config, there's only one telegram bot configured globally. OpenClaw doesn't natively support multiple telegram bots for different agents out of the box.\n\nThe user wants:\n- Willow users → bot 8562090487:AAGTrtdu8hP3WV4UYjldnCES-e9f2_dxHF0\n- Dixie users → bot 7225780511:AAH9B0StUH7vd26ewDXpuB698YB1l60OXbc\n\nOptions:\n1. **Single bot approach** - Use one bot for all, but route messages based on some identifier (not natively supported)\n2. **Multiple OpenClaw gateways** - Run separate gateway instances with different configs (complex)\n3. **Agent-specific routing** - Custom code to route messages based on the bot used\n\nActually, the simplest solution would be to have users message the bot, and in the pairing process, the system automatically associates them with their agent based on their StudyClaw account.\n\nWait - the user said \"All users who chose Willow during onboarding will message their agents same bot\". This means:\n- Dixie agent users → use Dixie bot\n- Willow agent users → use Willow bot\n\nBut OpenClaw is currently set up with one main agent. The student agents are separate.\n\nLet me think about this more practically:\n1. The OpenClaw gateway runs with one main agent (your agent: main)\n2. Each student agent (like Willow for martinez.a.richard@gmail.com) is a separate agent session\n3. To have separate bots, we'd need to either:\n   - Run multiple gateways (one per agent)\n   - Have some kind of routing logic\n\nActually, looking at the architecture - each student agent in OpenClaw might be able to have its own telegram configuration. Let me check if student agents can have their own channel configs.","thinkingSignature":"9a4c3b5d36cd067bbdd5a2ef14dc3d1668a0f2954fa02c57483471ea2ee2e876"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_8x9wmzidyirl_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/ubuntu/.nvm/versions/node/v24.14.0/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md | grep -A 20 \"per-agent\" | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":33737,"output":448,"cacheRead":13464,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47649,"cost":{"input":0.0101211,"output":0.0005376,"cacheRead":0.00040391999999999994,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.011062619999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773975741403}}
{"type":"message","id":"c2bbecbe","parentId":"729dae5c","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:41.154Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_8x9wmzidyirl_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"See [Multi-Agent](/concepts/multi-agent) and [full reference](/gateway/configuration-reference#multi-agent-routing) for binding rules and per-agent access profiles.\n\n  </Accordion>\n\n  <Accordion title=\"Split config into multiple files ($include)\">\n    Use `$include` to organize large configs:\n\n    ```json5\n    // ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json\n    {\n      gateway: { port: 18789 },\n      agents: { $include: \"./agents.json5\" },\n      broadcast: {\n        $include: [\"./clients/a.json5\", \"./clients/b.json5\"],\n      },\n    }\n    ```\n\n    - **Single file**: replaces the containing object\n    - **Array of files**: deep-merged in order (later wins)\n    - **Sibling keys**: merged after includes (override included values)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"See [Multi-Agent](/concepts/multi-agent) and [full reference](/gateway/configuration-reference#multi-agent-routing) for binding rules and per-agent access profiles.\n\n  </Accordion>\n\n  <Accordion title=\"Split config into multiple files ($include)\">\n    Use `$include` to organize large configs:\n\n    ```json5\n    // ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json\n    {\n      gateway: { port: 18789 },\n      agents: { $include: \"./agents.json5\" },\n      broadcast: {\n        $include: [\"./clients/a.json5\", \"./clients/b.json5\"],\n      },\n    }\n    ```\n\n    - **Single file**: replaces the containing object\n    - **Array of files**: deep-merged in order (later wins)\n    - **Sibling keys**: merged after includes (override included values)","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773975761152}}
{"type":"message","id":"13d50e89","parentId":"c2bbecbe","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:45.596Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me check the multi-agent routing docs to see if we can configure per-agent telegram settings.","thinkingSignature":"00694ef75be60278e1723bcb705dd01a8745496389f9174ae1d4ddc9da433d99"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_rdttzijmkjup_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/ubuntu/.nvm/versions/node/v24.14.0/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md | grep -B5 -A 30 \"per-agent\" | head -60"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":34372,"output":89,"cacheRead":13464,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47925,"cost":{"input":0.010311599999999999,"output":0.0001068,"cacheRead":0.00040391999999999994,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.01082232}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773975761156}}
{"type":"message","id":"92d13367","parentId":"13d50e89","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:45.613Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_rdttzijmkjup_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"`\"host\"` is blocked. `\"container:<id>\"` is blocked by default unless you explicitly set\n`sandbox.docker.dangerouslyAllowContainerNamespaceJoin: true` (break-glass).\n\n**Inbound attachments** are staged into `media/inbound/*` in the active workspace.\n\n**`docker.binds`** mounts additional host directories; global and per-agent binds are merged.\n\n**Sandboxed browser** (`sandbox.browser.enabled`): Chromium + CDP in a container. noVNC URL injected into system prompt. Does not require `browser.enabled` in `openclaw.json`.\nnoVNC observer access uses VNC auth by default and OpenClaw emits a short-lived token URL (instead of exposing the password in the shared URL).\n\n- `allowHostControl: false` (default) blocks sandboxed sessions from targeting the host browser.\n- `network` defaults to `openclaw-sandbox-browser` (dedicated bridge network). Set to `bridge` only when you explicitly want global bridge connectivity.\n- `cdpSourceRange` optionally restricts CDP ingress at the container edge to a CIDR range (for example `172.21.0.1/32`).\n- `sandbox.browser.binds` mounts additional host directories into the sandbox browser container only. When set (including `[]`), it replaces `docker.binds` for the browser container.\n- Launch defaults are defined in `scripts/sandbox-browser-entrypoint.sh` and tuned for container hosts:\n  - `--remote-debugging-address=127.0.0.1`\n  - `--remote-debugging-port=<derived from OPENCLAW_BROWSER_CDP_PORT>`\n  - `--user-data-dir=${HOME}/.chrome`\n  - `--no-first-run`\n  - `--no-default-browser-check`\n  - `--disable-3d-apis`\n  - `--disable-gpu`\n  - `--disable-software-rasterizer`\n  - `--disable-dev-shm-usage`\n  - `--disable-background-networking`\n  - `--disable-features=TranslateUI`\n  - `--disable-breakpad`\n  - `--disable-crash-reporter`\n  - `--renderer-process-limit=2`\n  - `--no-zygote`\n  - `--metrics-recording-only`\n  - `--disable-extensions` (default enabled)\n  - `--disable-3d-apis`, `--disable-software-rasterizer`, and `--disable-gpu` are\n    enabled by default and can be disabled with\n    `OPENCLAW_BROWSER_DISABLE_GRAPHICS_FLAGS=0` if WebGL/3D usage requires it.\n  - `OPENCLAW_BROWSER_DISABLE_EXTENSIONS=0` re-enables extensions if your workflow\n--\n```bash\nscripts/sandbox-setup.sh           # main sandbox image\nscripts/sandbox-browser-setup.sh   # optional browser image\n```\n\n### `agents.list` (per-agent overrides)\n\n```json5\n{\n  agents: {\n    list: [\n      {\n        id: \"main\",\n        default: true,\n        name: \"Main Agent\",\n        workspace: \"~/.openclaw/workspace\",\n        agentDir: \"~/.openclaw/agents/main/agent\",\n        model: \"anthropic/claude-opus-4-6\", // or { primary, fallbacks }\n        params: { cacheRetention: \"none\" }, // overrides matching defaults.models params by key\n        identity: {\n          name: \"Samantha\",\n          theme: \"helpful sloth\",\n          emoji: \"🦥\","}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"`\"host\"` is blocked. `\"container:<id>\"` is blocked by default unless you explicitly set\n`sandbox.docker.dangerouslyAllowContainerNamespaceJoin: true` (break-glass).\n\n**Inbound attachments** are staged into `media/inbound/*` in the active workspace.\n\n**`docker.binds`** mounts additional host directories; global and per-agent binds are merged.\n\n**Sandboxed browser** (`sandbox.browser.enabled`): Chromium + CDP in a container. noVNC URL injected into system prompt. Does not require `browser.enabled` in `openclaw.json`.\nnoVNC observer access uses VNC auth by default and OpenClaw emits a short-lived token URL (instead of exposing the password in the shared URL).\n\n- `allowHostControl: false` (default) blocks sandboxed sessions from targeting the host browser.\n- `network` defaults to `openclaw-sandbox-browser` (dedicated bridge network). Set to `bridge` only when you explicitly want global bridge connectivity.\n- `cdpSourceRange` optionally restricts CDP ingress at the container edge to a CIDR range (for example `172.21.0.1/32`).\n- `sandbox.browser.binds` mounts additional host directories into the sandbox browser container only. When set (including `[]`), it replaces `docker.binds` for the browser container.\n- Launch defaults are defined in `scripts/sandbox-browser-entrypoint.sh` and tuned for container hosts:\n  - `--remote-debugging-address=127.0.0.1`\n  - `--remote-debugging-port=<derived from OPENCLAW_BROWSER_CDP_PORT>`\n  - `--user-data-dir=${HOME}/.chrome`\n  - `--no-first-run`\n  - `--no-default-browser-check`\n  - `--disable-3d-apis`\n  - `--disable-gpu`\n  - `--disable-software-rasterizer`\n  - `--disable-dev-shm-usage`\n  - `--disable-background-networking`\n  - `--disable-features=TranslateUI`\n  - `--disable-breakpad`\n  - `--disable-crash-reporter`\n  - `--renderer-process-limit=2`\n  - `--no-zygote`\n  - `--metrics-recording-only`\n  - `--disable-extensions` (default enabled)\n  - `--disable-3d-apis`, `--disable-software-rasterizer`, and `--disable-gpu` are\n    enabled by default and can be disabled with\n    `OPENCLAW_BROWSER_DISABLE_GRAPHICS_FLAGS=0` if WebGL/3D usage requires it.\n  - `OPENCLAW_BROWSER_DISABLE_EXTENSIONS=0` re-enables extensions if your workflow\n--\n```bash\nscripts/sandbox-setup.sh           # main sandbox image\nscripts/sandbox-browser-setup.sh   # optional browser image\n```\n\n### `agents.list` (per-agent overrides)\n\n```json5\n{\n  agents: {\n    list: [\n      {\n        id: \"main\",\n        default: true,\n        name: \"Main Agent\",\n        workspace: \"~/.openclaw/workspace\",\n        agentDir: \"~/.openclaw/agents/main/agent\",\n        model: \"anthropic/claude-opus-4-6\", // or { primary, fallbacks }\n        params: { cacheRetention: \"none\" }, // overrides matching defaults.models params by key\n        identity: {\n          name: \"Samantha\",\n          theme: \"helpful sloth\",\n          emoji: \"🦥\",","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773975765611}}
