{"type":"message","id":"0dbc1ddb","parentId":"b885e98f","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:02:54.443Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_w59mhyyg7mea_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All channels support DM policies and group policies:\n`channels.defaults.groupPolicy` sets the default when a provider's `groupPolicy` is unset.\nIf a provider block is missing entirely (`channels.<provider>` absent), runtime group policy falls back to `allowlist` (fail-closed) with a startup warning.\nUse `channels.modelByChannel` to pin specific channel IDs to a model. Values accept `provider/model` or configured model aliases. The channel mapping applies when a session does not already have a model override (for example, set via `/model`).\n  channels: {\nUse `channels.defaults` for shared group-policy and heartbeat behavior across providers:\n  channels: {\n- `channels.defaults.groupPolicy`: fallback group policy when a provider-level `groupPolicy` is unset.\n- `channels.defaults.heartbeat.showOk`: include healthy channel statuses in heartbeat output.\n- `channels.defaults.heartbeat.showAlerts`: include degraded/error statuses in heartbeat output."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":10,"aggregated":"All channels support DM policies and group policies:\n`channels.defaults.groupPolicy` sets the default when a provider's `groupPolicy` is unset.\nIf a provider block is missing entirely (`channels.<provider>` absent), runtime group policy falls back to `allowlist` (fail-closed) with a startup warning.\nUse `channels.modelByChannel` to pin specific channel IDs to a model. Values accept `provider/model` or configured model aliases. The channel mapping applies when a session does not already have a model override (for example, set via `/model`).\n  channels: {\nUse `channels.defaults` for shared group-policy and heartbeat behavior across providers:\n  channels: {\n- `channels.defaults.groupPolicy`: fallback group policy when a provider-level `groupPolicy` is unset.\n- `channels.defaults.heartbeat.showOk`: include healthy channel statuses in heartbeat output.\n- `channels.defaults.heartbeat.showAlerts`: include degraded/error statuses in heartbeat output.","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773975774441}}
{"type":"message","id":"71da041b","parentId":"0dbc1ddb","timestamp":"2026-03-20T03:03:09.803Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Based on my research, OpenClaw doesn't natively support multiple telegram bots per agent in a single gateway instance. The telegram channel is configured globally.\n\nHowever, I can suggest a practical solution:1. **Option 1: Single bot with smart routing** - All users message one bot, and we route based on some identifier (like a code they include)\n\n2. **Option 2: Multiple gateways** - Run separate OpenClaw gateway processes, each with a different bot token and agent\n\n3. **Option 3: Keep it simple** - Use the existing setup where all users pair through the main bot, and they're automatically routed to their correct agent based on their StudyClaw account\n\nActually, thinking about it more - the pairing system might already handle this! When a user pairs via telegram, OpenClaw associates that telegram chat with their agent session. So even with one bot, different users would have separate isolated conversations.\n\nLet me explain this to the user - they might be overcomplicating it. The current setup likely already does what they want!","thinkingSignature":"ad080b04012dbdbf8f754a8ee87a2454b2a9d3920ac81b92dbea608e37f35c7e"},{"type":"text","text":"Here's the thing — OpenClaw's current architecture uses **one gateway with one telegram bot**. However, the **pairing system already handles isolation**:\n\nWhen a user messages the bot and pairs:\n- Their Telegram chat gets linked to their specific agent (Willow or Dixie)\n- Each user's conversation is already **separate and isolated**\n- They can't see each other's chats\n\n**So you might not need separate bots!**\n\nThe flow would be:\n1. User signs up → chooses \"Willow\" or \"Dixie\" as their agent\n2. They message the bot → get pairing code\n3. Enter code in app → Telegram now routes to their specific agent\n4. They chat with Willow/Dixie — fully isolated from other users\n\n**If you still want separate bots** (e.g., different bot names/avatars), you'd need to run **multiple gateway instances** — one per bot/agent. That's more complex to set up.\n\nWhat's your preference — test the single-bot flow first, or set up separate bots per agent?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":35479,"output":433,"cacheRead":13464,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":49376,"cost":{"input":0.010643699999999999,"output":0.0005195999999999999,"cacheRead":0.00040391999999999994,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.01156722}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773975774445}}
